nce music, and Värttinä, an ensemble that highlights women's vocal traditions. Analyzing the multilayered processes—musical, institutional, political, and commercial—that have shaped and are shaped by new folk music in Finland, Ramnarine gives us an entirely new understanding of the connections between music, place, and identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFolk musiczFinlandxHistory and criticism. 0aMusic and globalizationzFinland. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aglobalization, nationalism, finland, landscape, bard, oral narratives, legend, folklore, folk music, soundscapes, nature, kalevala, creativity, national identity, fiddling, social anthropology, ethnomusicology, performance, musicians, jpp, fiddle, dance, varttina, vocal, women, gender, tradition, place, representation, borrowing, lonnrot, myth, repertoire, authenticity, transformation, revival, kaustinen festival, sibelius academy, urban, karelianism, helsinki, saami, tango, ireland, ownership, capitalism, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226704043423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226704043/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles